occurrences.line_text: Till death make one end of my dayes and miserie.
Short end of sorrowes they thereby did find;
Can haue no end, nor hope of my desire,
From the worlds end, through many a bitter stowre:
Vnto these Sprights, to bring to perfect end.
Deepe busied bout worke of wondrous end,
Vnwares haue prest: for either fatall end,
But yet the end is not. There Merlin stayd,
And the sad end of her sweet Marinell.
The fearefull end of his auengement sad,
All things decay in time, and to their end do draw.
What end vnto that fearefull Damozell,
And at the twelue monethes end should bring their names
Her will to win vnto his wished end.
To whom I leuell all my labours end,
In sewing deeds of armes, my liues and labours end.
Gaue them safe conduct, till to end they came:
One may his iourney bring too soone to euill end.
And at the vpper end of that faire rowme,
At last she spyde at that roomes vpper end,
And her faire locks vp stared stiffe on end,
Abode, to weet what end would come of all.
At this same furrowes end, till a new day:
For discord harder is to end then to begin.
The which most often end in bloudshed and in warre.
Lo recreant (sayd he) the fruitlesse end
Did beare them both to fell auenges end,
That doth ill cause or euill end enure:
Amongst them all this end he did decree;
Therefore desirous th'end of all their dayes
Yet is as nigh his end, as he that most doth playne.
Let forth his wearie ghost and made an end of strife.
Resolu'd to end it one or other way;
He gan to faint, toward the battels end,
To make an end of all that did withstand:
They weened sure the warre was at an end,
And th'end of both likewise of both their ends.
So nought may be esteemed happie till the end.
All which when Blandamour from end to end
All which when Blandamour from end to end
The cause and end thereof: but all in vaine;
The end whereof and daungerous euent
Thereby to make their loues beginning, their liues end.
But toward th'end Sir Arthegall renewed
Full glad of so good end, to them drew nere,
Ran, till he came to th'end of all his way,
Shall death be th'end, or ought else worse, aread.
I me resolu'd the vtmost end to proue,
She staid not the vtmost end thereof to try,
I will deferre the end vntill another tide.
In th'end she her vnto that place did guide,
Till she had duld the sting, which in her tongs end grew.
And for defence thereof, on th'other end
So ended he his tale, where I this Canto end.
But let me die and end my daies attone,
[here, in 1609, 'The end of the Fourth Booke.']
To sit in his owne seate, his cause to end,
Immoueable, resistlesse, without end.
Perhaps I may all further quarrell end,
And towards th'end, grew greater in his might,
Together met, of all to make an end.
And turne we here to this faire furrowes end
Ne other end their fury would afford,
Heard to the end, she was right sore bestad,
Till to the Bridges further end she past,
All which when he vnto the end had heard,
The end whereof, and all the long euent,
All which when she vnto the end had heard,
Which was the roote of all, end your reuenge on mee.
Before directed by his Lord; to th'end
Doubting sad end of principle vnsound:
Wayting what end would be of that same daunger drad.
For if I liue till those ten daies haue end,
Pounching me with the butt end of his speare,
In th'end his kyndly courtesie to proue,
But th'vtmost end perforce for to aby,
That in another Canto shall to end be brought.
An hard aduenture with vnhappie end;
Yet nought the nearer to his iourneys end;
To leape into the same after our liues end.
And wretched end, which still attendeth on her.
To some hid end to make more easie way,
With that the foole, which did that end awayte,
And make one end of him without ruth or remorse.
My life will by his death haue lamentable end.
The end whereof Ile keepe vntill another cast.
Ne durst abide the daunger of the end;
Since neither is endamadg'd much thereby.
Ne ought he car'd, whom he endamaged
That neuer more he mote endammadge wight
That deadly dint of steele endanger may:
Which way he enter might, without endangerment.
Ere she had ended all, she gan to faint:
If not well ended at our dying day.
And ended all her woe in quiet death.
When he thus ended had his sorrowing,
Which hauing ended, after him she flyeth swift.
Here ended Brutus sacred progenie,
Ne yet has ended: for it was a great
Who hauing ended with that Squire of Dames
Betwixt vs both vnknowne. So ended Paridell.
In loue were either ended or begunne:
And when the next shall likewise ended bee,
Where when she saw that cruell war so ended,
After the proofe of prowesse ended well,
And now by this their feast all being ended,
For he last ended, hauing first begonne.
This being ended thus, and all agreed,
Which ended, then his bloudy banket should beginne.
That harder may be ended, then begonne.
So ended he his tale, where I this Canto end.
And now by this the feast was throughly ended,
When they thus ended had, the Knight began;
With bitter strokes it both began, and ended.
But where ye ended haue, now I begin
Shall more conueniently in other place be ended.
When thus that shepherd ended had his speach,
Like to Osyris in all iust endeuer.
Him forth through infinite endeuour to haue sought.
At least it faire endeuour will apply.
Did her espy, and through my good endeuour
His best endeuour, and his daily paine,
But he endeuoured with speeches milde
Endeuouring my dreadded name to raise
Yet ought mens good endeuours them confirme,
And with Sans-foyes dead dowry you endew.
For euery shape on him he could endew:
But most of all, those three did her with gifts endew.
The club of Iustice dread, with kingly powre endewed.
That hast with borrowed plumes thy selfe endewed,
O soueraigne Queene, whose prayse I would endite,
Endite I would as dewtie doth excite;
That neuer so deserued to endite.
And counted but a recreant Knight, with endles shame.
God helpe the man so wrapt in Errours endlesse traine.
And that in endlesse error she might euer stray.
Such endlesse richesse, and so sumptuous shew;
From wandring Stygian shores, where it doth endlesse moue.
The house of endlesse paine is built thereby,
Theseus condemned to endlesse slouth by law,
Of endlesse life he might him not depriue,
Here endlesse penance for one fault I pay,
Besides the endlesse routs of wretched thralles,
Did breed him endlesse labour to subdew:
And thousand feends that doe them endlesse paine
Brings them to ioyous rest and endlesse blis.
Is, as it were for endlesse memory
A worke of labour long, and endlesse prayse:
And be for all chast Dames an endlesse moniment.
Which thee to endlesse bale captiued lead.
In which full many soules do endlesse waile and weepe.
And wondred at his endlesse exercise,
And endlesse moniments of his great good:
Which with incessaunt force and endlesse hate,
Makes for him endlesse mone, and euermore
Of which, that field for endlesse memory,
In his chiefe Church, for endlesse moniments
Into the balefull house of endlesse night,
To be captiued in endlesse duraunce
Here to account the endlesse progenie
In endlesse rancks along enraunged were,
To whom sweet Poets verse hath giuen endlesse date.
And be partakers of thy endlesse fame.
Endlesse renowm, that more then death is to be sought.
Let vgly shame and endlesse infamy
And robd the world of threasure endlesse deare,
But through the endlesse world did wander wide,
Whom seeking euer since with endlesse paines,
And gan their endlesse happinesse enuye,
With endlesse cost, to be th'Almighties see;
And endlesse memorie, that mote excell,
Loose so immortall glory, and so endlesse gaines.
O What an endlesse worke haue I in hand,
Albe they endlesse seeme in estimation,
And causde great sackes with endlesse riches fraught,
Adorned all with gemmes of endlesse price,
To whom for endlesse horrour of his shame,
To tread an endlesse trace, withouten guyde,
And all this land with endlesse losse to ouerflow.
Ne ought was tyred with his endlesse toyles,
That endlesse were to tell. The Elfin Knight,
That who from East to West will endlong seeke,
To seeke her endlong, both by sea and lond.
Gaue me a shield, in which he did endosse
And her endowd with royall maiestye:
And euery one her with a grace endowes:
To die againe? all ends that was begonne.
The ends of all their knots, that none might see,
And eke so short, that seemd their ends out shortly came.
And th'end of both likewise of both their ends.
But of occasion, with th'occasion ends;
Which when the Damzell, who those deadly ends
And nature me endu'd with plenteous dowre,
All which when she with hard enduraunce had
For him she late endur'd; she speakes no more
The lesser pangs can beare, who hath endur'd the chiefe.
Who hath endur'd the whole, can beare each part.
That he his paine endur'd, as seeming now more light.
I haue endur'd, and tasted many a bloudy wound.
And manly limbs endur'd with little care
That eye mote not the same endure to vew.
That she could not endure that dolefull stound,
Could not endure th'vnwonted sunne to view;
That he could not endure so cruell cace,
Which else could not endure those beames bright,
That as a law for euer should endure;
Hardly could he endure his hardiment,
But he would not endure that wofull theame
Your cruell eyes endure so pitteous sight,
The faithfull steele such treason no'uld endure,
So goodly workemanship should not endure:
Would not endure to be so vile disdaind,
Die rather would he, then endure that same.
Cannot endure, but needs it must be wrackt
Ne certes can that friendship long endure,
Hope to endure, sith workes of heauenly wits
And that he should not long on foote endure,
What yron courage euer could endure,
Durst not endure their sight, but fled from place to place.
Ne ought could them endure, but all they cleft or brast.
Did well endure her womanish disdaine,
That his great force vnable to endure,
To make them to endure the pains, did them torment.
Endure to trauell, nor one foote to frame:
Ne would endure the daunger of their might,
And damned to endure this direfull smart,
Addeem'd me to endure this penaunce sore;
That neuer more they should endure the shew
And his new Lady it endured not.
Which haue endured many a dreadfull stowre,
His long endured famine needed more reliefe.
Which he endured in his late restraint,
After long wayes and perilous paines endured,
And for his dearest sake endured sore,
Hath no lesse griefe endured for your gentle sake.
Which he in chace endured hath, now nigh breathlesse.
For from the first he to the last endured,
This feeble brest endured hath, but none
Yet they endured all with patience milde,
So all that euer yet I haue endured,
Which he endured had through daungerous debate.
Who all this while endured for her sake,
And toyle endured, sith I left him last
And had endured many a dreadfull stoure
That none without the same enduren can.
That with his souce, which none enduren dare,
No loue so lasting then, that may enduren long.
Not made of steele, nor of enduring bras,
Had past the paines of hell, and long enduring night.
For not of wood, nor of enduring bras,
Which thousand sprights with long enduring paines
And ouer-wrestled his strong enemie,
That art thus foully fled from famous enemie?
Vnluckie Mayd to seeke her enemie!
For dread of their deuouring enemie,
And nimbler handed, then his enemie,
All were it to his mortall enemie,
When morning altars purgd with enemies life,
And warning giue, that enemies conspyre,
But griefe and wrath, that be her enemies,
But thousand enemies about vs raue,
She triumphed on death, in enemies despight.
And secretly his enemies did slay:
So farre he past amongst his enemies band,
And cruell enemies increased more;
That thorough some more mighty enemies wrong,
Whom soone as his three enemies did vew,
Glauncing askew, as if his enemies
Ne priuate iarre, ne spite of enemis
And fretting griefe the enemy of life;
To bath in bloud of faithlesse enemy;
And felly gnarre, vntill dayes enemy
Till that their cruell cursed enemy,
Since late she saw him fall before his enemy.
And doubted, whether his late enemy
That neuer yet encountred enemy,
Without bloudshed, and where the enemy
But naught he car'd for friend or enemy,
And is he vanquisht by his tyrant enemy?
The wicked stroke did wound his enemy,
With her vnrighteous enemy to fight,
Whom well he wist to be some enemy,
No wound, which warlike hand of enemy
That cursed caytiue, my strong enemy,
Wrapt in eternall silence farre from enemyes.
But all so soone as his enfeebled spright
Still when as he enfeebled was, him cherisht,
With that like one enfelon'd or distraught,
But more enfierced through his currish play,
Enflam'd with fury and fiers hardy-hed,
Exceeding rage enflam'd the furious beast,
All sodainely enflam'd with furious fit,
That seemd him to enflame on euery side:
For all the crest a Dragon did enfold
Ay me, how many perils doe enfold
In which a Serpent did himselfe enfold,
The which O pardon me thus to enfold
Which did themselues emongst the leaues enfold,
Whose hideous tayle his left foot did enfold,
In which she meant him warelesse to enfold,
That with her wreathed taile her middle did enfold.
Enfolding said, And liues yet Amyas?
These sixe would me enforce by oddes of might,
So did these two through all the field their foes enforce.
Strongly did Zele her haynous fact enforce,
Till strong constraint did her thereto enforce.
Though they enforce themselues, cannot attaine.
Enforced them their forward footing to reuoke.
Ne will enforced be with maisterdome or might.
That they which lead him, soone enforced beene
That backeward he enforced him to fall:
The idle stroke, enforcing furious way,
And by hard meanes enforcing her to stay,
He could enforme, and them reduce aright,
Am now enforst a far vnfitter taske,
Enforst to seeke some couert nigh at hand,
Enforst her purple beast with all her might
Feare gaue her wings, and rage enforst my flight;
And Vortiger enforst the kingdome to aband.
Was for like need enforst to disaray:
Yet when as foes enforst, or friends sought ayde,
Yet praise likewise deserue good thewes, enforst with paine.
Which I enforst to beare though to my paine,
But more enforst my paine, the more my plaints to heare.
Vnlesse that I were thereunto enforst.
Ere long enforst to breath his vtmost blast,
With foule enfouldred smoake and flashing fire,
Thy workes for wealth, and life for gold engage.
Tho each to other did his faith engage,
For which his faith with her he fast engaged,
The pledge of faith, her hand engaged held,
As when that diuelish yron Engin wrought
The fierce threeforked engin making way,
His craftie engin, and as he had sayd,
To shunne the engin of his meant decay;
The Engin fiercely flying forth, doth teare
Therefore this craftie engine he did frame,
The wicked engine through false influence,
And subtile engines bet from batteree,
Hewen out of Adamant rocke with engines keene,
That seemes rough Masons hand with engines keene
By subtile engins and malitious slight
Thereto his subtile engins he does bend
Their wicked engins they against it bent:
Her crafty engins to her close intent.
He found, then his false engins fast he plyde,
And all the engins of her wit display;
Engirt about, ne other garment wore:
Saint George of mery England, the signe of victoree.
Cambridge or Oxford, Englands goodly beames.
And thou faire ymp, sprong out from English race,
Didst thou behight me borne of English blood,
And th'English Bath, and eke the german Spau,
Dan Chaucer, well of English vndefyled,
And water all the English soile throughout;
Of Scots and English both, that tyned on his strand.
Swift Awniduff, which of the English man
And balefull Oure, late staind with English blood:
Whose grieued mindes, which choler did englut,
And the deepe wound more deepe engord her hart,
Well hoped she the beast engor'd had beene,
When rancour doth with rage him once engore,
That euer hand should dare for to engore
But did his hart with bitter thoughts engore,
Her selfe quite through the bodie doth engore,
Deadly engored of a great wild Bore,
The tast of bloud of some engored beast,
Then fraught with rancour, and engorged ire,
That deepe engorgeth all this worldes pray:
Whereof did grow her first engraffed paine;
This my deare daughters deepe engraffed ill,
Which that same witch had in this forme engraft,
So both together fiers engrasped bee,
Twixt his two mighty armes engrasped fast,
In seemely sort their corses to engraue,
So both agree their bodies to engraue;
For Loue his loftie triumphes to engraue,
He did engraue, and muchell bloud did spend,
Had long while laboured it to engraue:
Of his true hart so firmely was engraued,
How he the name of one engrauen had,
That my engreeued mind could find no rest,
Which spitefull words she sore engrieu'd to heare,
Faire Malecasta, whose engrieued spright
But she was more engrieued, and replide;
Seeing his worke now wasted deepe engrieued was.
Did greatly solace his engrieued mind.
The which afflicted his engrieued mind;
And well disburdened her engrieued brest,
With grace from her, whose loue his heart hath sore engrieued.
To see friends graue, the[m] dead the graue selfe to engrosse.
Engrost with mud, which did them foule agrise,
The face of heauen, and the cleare aire engrost,
Like an huge Aetn' of deepe engulfed griefe,
In th'huge abysse of his engulfing graue,
His glory did enhaunce, and pompous pride display.
But wondrous paine, that did the more enhaunce
That her enhaunced hand she downe can soft withdraw.
Who nought aghast, his mightie hand enhaunst:
There also was king Croesus, that enhaunst
Both of them high attonce their hands enhaunst,
They met Prince Arthure with Sir Enias,
Shame would be hid. But whenas Enias
Which he had borne of his bold enimee.
And proou'd your strength on a strong enimie,
To aide his friends, or fray his enimies:
Or enimies powre hath now captiued you,
His precious horne, sought of his enimies
Then made he head against his enimies,
The enimies of Temperaunce
And couetous aspectes, all cruell enimies.
When so him list his enimies to fray:
Triumphed oft against her enimis;
Watching to banish Care their enimy,
To be aueng'd each on his enimy.
Plaine, faithfull, true, and enimy of shame,
Each other bent his enimy to quell,
Or get his shield, his monstrous enimy
And shame t'auenge so weake an enimy;
As losse of time, and vertues enimy
For to all good he enimy was still.
As Hind from her, so she fled from her enimy.
Trust me, shall find no greater enimy,
And maistring might on enimy dismayd:
Of Troynouant, gainst force of enimy,
The lether-winged Bat, dayes enimy,
Bad those same sixe forbeare that single enimy.
Dy, who so list for him, he was loues enimy.
The enimy of peace, and author of all strife.
Great enimy to it, and to all the rest,
Sore trouble of an hainous enimy;
Which when his cruell enimy espyde,
So long vnwreaked of thine enimy?
Succour against her greedy enimy:
He there does now enioy eternall rest
In full content he there did long enioy,
Enioy the crowne, which they from Britons wonne
There wont faire Venus often to enioy
And life enioy for any composition.
And each his portion peaceably enioyd,
Enioyd an heritage of lasting peace,
Ioying his goddesse, and of her enioyd:
Sith I enioyd the gentlest Dame aliue;
Nath'lesse the same enioyed but short happy howre:
Where she enioyes sure peace for euermore,
Cupid their eldest brother; he enioyes
This penaunce, which enioyned is to me,
But soone as Furor was enlargd, she sought
Great mercy sure, for to enlarge a thrall,
Finding no meanes how I might vs enlarge,
How from that dungeon he might her enlarge:
Deuize how to enlarge him out of hould.
For nought may lessened nor enlarged bee,
The faire Poeana he enlarged free;
And now on earth it selfe enlarged has,
Or long enlargement of her painefull smart.
Were housed therewithin, whom he enlargen might.
Enlincked fast in wedlockes loyall bond,
And treasures of true loue enlocked beene,
That doth enlumine all these lesser fyres,
And with her light the earth enlumines cleare;
Three mightie en'mies did him most despight,
A triple warre with triple enmitee,
But wanted sword to wreake his enmitee.
And to him brought the shield, the cause of enmitie.
Debatefull strife, and cruell enmitie
That breathed strife and troublous enmitie;
And kindling coles of cruell enmitie,
From stirring vp their stormy enmitie,
For enmitie, that of no ill proceeds,
To stint all strife and troublous enmitie,
Where warres, and wreckes, and wicked enmitie
Pursew the end of their strong enmity,
What monstrous enmity prouoke we heare,
But rather stird to cruell enmity,
For in base mind nor friendship dwels nor enmity.
Neuer thenceforth to nourish enmity,
Against his praise to stirre vp enmitye
The knight was much enmoued with his speach,
That doest ennoble with immortall name
Nor more ennobled for their courtesie,
That warlike hands ennoblest with immortall name;
Enough is, that thy foe doth vanquisht stand
Who had enough, yet wished euer more;
Is not enough, that thrust from heauen dew
Is not enough thy euill life forespent?
Is not enough, that to this Ladie milde
He had enough, what need him care for more?
That speare is him enough to doen a thousand grone.
Is not enough foure quarters of a man,
Matter of merth enough, though there were none
And striue to passe (as she could well enough)
Is not enough, that I alone doe dye,
Enough to hold a foole in vaine delight:
More is more losse: one is enough to dy.
Yet thought himselfe not safe enough thereby,
Said, Gentle Dame, reward enough I weene
They two enough t'encounter an whole Regiment.
It's punishment enough, that all his shame doe see.
Which though I be not wise enough to frame,
